'''Emotional promiscuity''' has been addressed in both the [[Popular psychology|popular press]] as well as in [[scientific literature]]. 

In the popular press, there was a book published in 2007 entitled, ''Avoid the Heartbreak of Emotional Promiscuity,'' written by Brienne Murk.<ref>{{cite book|last=Murk|first=Brienne|title=Avoiding the Heartbreak of Emotional Promiscuity|year=2007|publisher=Regal Books}}</ref>  In her book, Murk argues that (a) guarding one's heart is required for staying pure, (b) emotions cannot be trusted, and (c) that young people must set physical and emotional boundaries.  Murk also attempts to discourage young people from having premarital sex and engaging in activities she deems impure. The book is written from a Christian perspective, and its assertions based on the author's religious interpretations.

In scientific literature, Jones (2011) examined the concept of ''Emotional Promiscuity'' as a [[Personality psychology|personality]]/[[Differential psychology|individual difference]] construct <ref>{{cite web|last=Jones|first=Daniel|title=Emotional Promiscuity: Consequences for health and well-being|url=https://circle.ubc.ca/handle/2429/37893|publisher=University of British Columbia|accessdate=November 25, 2012}}</ref> Jones defines emotional promiscuity as the predisposition to fall in love easily, fast, and often.  Such individuals tend to love the feeling of [[falling in love]], and want to be with many [[Romance (love)|romantic]] partners.

Emotional promiscuity can be assessed through [[Self-report study|self-report]] using the Emotional Promiscuity Scale (or EP Scale;<ref>{{cite book|last=Jones|first=Daniel|title=The Emotional Promiscuity Scale|year=2011|publisher=Handbook of Sexuality-Related Measures|location=New York, Routledge|isbn=0415801753|pages=226–227}}</ref> and is distinct from both [[Promiscuity|sexual promiscuity]] <ref>{{cite journal|last=Simpson|first=Jeffrey|author2=Gangestad, Steve|title=Individual differences in sociosexuality: Evidence for convergent and discriminant validity.|journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|year=1991|volume=60|pages=870–883|doi=10.1037/0022-3514.60.6.870}}</ref> and [[Attachment theory#Attachment patterns|anxious attachment]] <ref>{{cite journal|last=Hazan|first=C|author2=Shaver, Phillip|title=Romantic love conceptualized as an attachment process.|journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|year=1987|volume=52|pages=511–524|doi=10.1037/0022-3514.52.3.511|pmid=3572722}}</ref> 

In addition, emotional promiscuity poses a health risk when combined with sexual promiscuity.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Jones|first=Daniel|author2=Paulhus, Delroy|title=The role of emotional promiscuity in unprotected sex.  |journal=Psychology & Health|year=2012|volume=27|pages=1021–1035|doi=10.1080/08870446.2011.647819}}</ref>

In particular individuals who fall in love frequently and easily, and who are also comfortable with [[casual sex]], have many [[Safe sex|unprotected sexual]] partners. The authors argue this finding results from premature [[Trust (social sciences)|trust]] which eventuates into the faulty perception that protection is unnecessary.

