== L ==
{{glossary}}
{{term|term=La Guardia Committee |content=[[La Guardia Committee]]}}
{{defn|1944 [[New York Academy of Medicine]] report prepared for Mayor [[Fiorello LaGuardia]]'s commission, appointed in 1939 to study the effects of marihuana use in the US, that concluded the publicity concerning the catastrophic effects of marihuana smoking is unfounded, marihuana is not the determining factor in the commission of major crimes, marihuana smoking is not widespread among school children, and the [[gateway drug theory]] is without foundation. The report was condemned by "drug czar" [[Harry Anslinger]].}}
{{term|term=LEAP |content=[[Law Enforcement Action Partnership|LEAP]]}}
{{defn|Law Enforcement Action Partnership, formerly called Law Enforcement Against Prohibition, is an organization of retired police officers and law enforcement officials, formed in 2002, now with more than 180 speakers, representing 5,000 law enforcement members, and more than 100,000 supporters worldwide. [See [[cannabis rights organizations]].]}}
{{term|term=Leary v. United States |content=''[[Leary v. United States]]''}}
{{defn|1969 [[U.S. Supreme Court]] ruling that unanimously declared the [[Marihuana Tax Act of 1937]] to be unconstitutional. [[Prohibition of drugs|Prohibition]] of cannabis continued under [[Richard Nixon|Nixon]]'s 1970 [[Controlled Substances Act]], which placed cannabis in [[List of Schedule I drugs (US)|Schedule I]], prohibiting all uses.}}
{{term|term=legalization |content=[[legalization]]}}
{{defn|The process of removing the legal [[Prohibition of drugs|prohibition]] against cannabis.}}
{{term|term=Legalize It |content=''[[Legalize It]]''}}
{{defn|Song by [[Peter Tosh]] from an album of the same title, originally recorded in 1975, that was banned in Jamaica when it was released, and has since then become a [[cannabis culture]] anthem.}}
{{term|term=lid |content=lid}}
{{defn|A measured quantity of [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]], usually one ounce to 1 1/2 ounces, an amount that would fill a shoe box lid.<ref name="WeedBlog"/>}}
{{term|term=live resin |content=live resin}}
{{defn|Extracted fresh cannabis that is kept at freezing temperatures through the entire process, rather than dried.<ref name="Cannabis101">{{cite web | url=https://www.leafly.com/news/cannabis-101/what-is-live-resin-cannabis-concentrate | title=Cannabis 101: What Are Live Resin Cannabis Concentrates? | work=[[Leafly]] | date= | accessdate=December 10, 2017 | author=Bennett, Patrick }}</ref> [See [[cannabis edible]]s and extracts.]}}

{{glossary end}}

== M ==
[[File:Marijuana-Cannabis-Weed-Bud-Gram.jpg|thumb|right|Dried marijuana, typical of what is sold for drug use]]
{{glossary}}
{{term|term=ma |content=ma}}
{{defn|Chinese name for cannabis.<ref>{{citation|author=Jann Gumbiner Ph.D. |title=History of Cannabis in Ancient China|work=[[Psychology Today]]|date=May 10, 2011|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/the-teenage-mind/201105/history-cannabis-in-ancient-china}}</ref>}}
{{term|term=Madison Hempfest |content=[[Madison Hempfest]]}}
{{defn|See [[Great Midwest Marijuana Harvest Festival]].}}
{{term|term=magical brownie |content=[[magical brownie]]}}
{{defn|A slang name for a [[cannabis edible]].<ref name="Times2"/>}}
{{term|term=magic mushroom |content=[[magic mushroom]]}}
{{defn|Any of 186 species of psilocybin fungi, or psychedelic mushrooms, banned in the United States under Schedule I of the Controlled Substances Act. Used since prehistoric times as an [[entheogen]] for spiritual experiences, some cultures have used psilocybin mushrooms in their religious rites and ceremonies. [See [[cannabis culture]].]}}
{{term|term=mandatory minimum sentencing |content=[[mandatory minimum sentencing]]}}
{{defn|Laws that require offenders serve a predefined term for certain crimes, criticized for resulting in harsh sentencing and [[cruel and unusual punishment]].}}
{{term|term=marihuana or marijuana |content=[[Marihuana (word)|marihuana]] or [[Marijuana (word)|marijuana]]}}
{{defn|A slang word for [[cannabis]], the legal name in some jurisdictions.}}
{{term|term=Marihuana |content=''[[Marihuana (film)|Marihuana]]''}}
{{defn|1936 American [[Anti-marijuana campaigns|anti-marijuana propaganda]] film that depicts [[alcoholic drink]]s and cannabis use leading to tragedies, including pregnancy, police shootouts, and a [[Gateway drug theory|gateway]] to heroin use and a life of crime. [See [[Prohibition of drugs|prohibition]].]}}
{{term|term=Marihuana Tax Act |content=[[Marihuana Tax Act]]}}
{{defn|1937 U.S. law that prohibited cannabis for the first time, and was ruled unconstitutional by the Supreme Court in 1969 and replaced with President Nixon's [[Controlled Substances Act]]. [See [[Prohibition of drugs|prohibition]].]}}
{{term|term=marijuana prohibition |content=[[Prohibition of drugs|marijuana prohibition]]}}
{{defn|Laws in some jurisdictions banning the cultivation or sales of [[cannabis]] in an attempt to prevent its use. These bans are criticized because they create a black market and because enforcement is disproportionate in communities of color.<ref name="DrugWarCrimes"/><ref name="NewJimCrow"/>}}
{{term|term=marijuana refugee |content=[[marijuana refugee]]}}
{{defn|Term referring to people who have moved from one location to another due to cannabis [[Prohibition of drugs|prohibition]] laws, motivated by a desire to have legal access to cannabis to treat medical conditions for themselves or their family, or to legally consume cannabis for any other reason.}}
{{term|term=marijuana rights |content=[[marijuana rights]]}}
{{defn|The rights of people who consume cannabis include freedom of speech and freedom of religion, and the right to be free from employment and housing discrimination.}}
{{term|term=marijuana rights leaders |content=[[marijuana rights leaders]]}}
{{defn|See [[freedom fighter]].}}
{{term|term=Marinol |content=[[Marinol]]}}
{{defn|A synthetic [[cannabinoid]], tetrahydrocannabinol ([[Tetrahydrocannabinol|THC]]), also called dronabinol, produced by [[Insys Therapeutics]] and [[Solvay (company)|Solvay Pharmaceuticals]], sold legally in the United States under Schedule III of the [[Controlled Substances Act]], though natural THC is banned under Schedule I.}}
{{term|term=Mary Jane |content=[[Mary Jane (slang)|Mary Jane]]}}
{{defn|A slang name for [[cannabis]].<ref name=DEA/>}}
